    "creation_date" : 1378300386,
    "answer_id" : 18614858,
    "question_id" : 1590831,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>DONT: This is not a solution!</strong></p>\n\n<p>My first approach was:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public int longToInt(long theLongOne) {\n  return Long.valueOf(theLongOne).intValue();\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>But that merely just casts the long to an int, potentially creating new <code>Long</code> instances or retrieving them from the Long pool.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>The drawbacks</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p><code>Long.valueOf</code> creates a new <code>Long</code> instance if the number is not within <code>Long</code>'s pool range [-128, 127].</p></li>\n<li><p>The <code>intValue</code> implementation does nothing more than:</p>\n\n<pre><code>return (int)value;\n</code></pre></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>So this can be considered even worse than just casting the <code>long</code> to <code>int</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1175385,
        "reputation" : 23793,
        "user_id" : 1151521,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 77,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aa1c3ce93537e4a6f189e2b1dd41a925?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Aleksandr Dubinsky",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1151521/aleksandr-dubinsky"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 7,
      "creation_date" : 1509097391,
      "post_id" : 32869210,
      "comment_id" : 80891480,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "We also have <code>addExact</code> and <code>multiplyExact</code>. Of note is that division (<code>MIN_VALUE&#47;-1</code>) and absolute value (<code>abs(MIN_VALUE)</code>) do not have safe convenience methods."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 5630551,
        "reputation" : 1996,
        "user_id" : 4457630,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/9KTaN.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Yamashiro Rion",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4457630/yamashiro-rion"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1556878518,
      "post_id" : 32869210,
      "comment_id" : 98586244,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "But what&#39;s a difference of using <code>Math.toIntExact()</code> instead of usual cast to <code>int</code>? The implementation of <code>Math.toIntExact()</code> just casts <code>long</code> to <code>int</code>."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1189453,
        "reputation" : 8159,
        "user_id" : 1162647,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 69,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/pCSol.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Pierre-Antoine",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1162647/pierre-antoine"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 5630551,
        "reputation" : 1996,
        "user_id" : 4457630,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/9KTaN.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Yamashiro Rion",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4457630/yamashiro-rion"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 3,
      "creation_date" : 1556885713,
      "post_id" : 32869210,
      "comment_id" : 98589819,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@YamashiroRion Actually the implementation of toIntExact first checks whether the cast would lead to an overflow, in which case it throws an ArithmeticException. Only if the cast is safe it then performs cast from long to int which it returns. In other words, if you try to cast a long number that cannot be represented as int (eg any number strictly above 2 147 483 647) it will throw an ArithmeticException. If you do the same with a simple cast, your resulting int value will be wrong."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1435828,
        "reputation" : 288,
        "user_id" : 1357233,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/016a21d7dad1cffa1fa74b8929ca4904?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Vitaliy Kulikov",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1357233/vitaliy-kulikov"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1755161307,
      "post_id" : 32869210,
      "comment_id" : 140664765,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "It is not correct. Math.toIntExact should be used, then you need to encode the long positive/negative (not in the same time) number to store it in int, so save size using sign byte.     Math.toIntExact(Integer.MAX_VALUE + 1) will return -2147483648.    So, next, you should decode this number into long using  Integer.toUnsignedLong."
    } ],
